page.title: 09WICK NATURE RESERVE
page.content: The Nature Reserve begins at the bottom of Wick Hill near the A414 and extends to Hazeleigh Wood.It covers 16 acres.The reserve is mainly for wild- life and is an excellent place to see insects,birds,animals and trees.Twenty six species of butterfly are there.The rarest are the White Letter Hairstreak and the White Admiral. The reserve runs along a disused railway track and is cared for by vol- untary workers.The last train ran in 1953.There is a great variety of trees -the rarest being the Field Maple,Horn beam and the Wild Service.Apple,plum & pear also grow.It is thought that they germinated from stones and pips thrown out of carriage windows.The Chiffchaff one of the rarer birds is frequently seen.It migrates to Spain every Winter
